\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size larger
Wavy is primarily intended to be a visual-to-sound substitution system.
 However it is designed to be an easily extendable framework in order to
 develop other types of sensory substitution system.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size larger
So what's the difference with Wavy and why another sensory substitution
 package ? Others sensory substitution systems are coded in C/C++ or Java
 programming language and are designed to be used as an end user application.
 Instead, Wavy is designed as a framework to develop new ideas in the sensory
 substitution field.
 Main goals are
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\size larger
using an agile and multi-platform language
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\size larger
developping a general framework for sensory substitution with great extendable
 capabilities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\size larger
to be very flexible in context of usage (gaming, scientific research, R&D
 or why not real life)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size larger
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size larger
Python was choose for its ability to be very powerfull and extensible.
 It favorise experimentation and rapid developpment of new ideas/features.
 It provide a large collection of quality standard and third-party packages
 in many fields (GUI, games, numerical computation etc.).
 After prototyping, code can be profiled and bottlnecks could be moved in
 C/C++ code.
\end_layout

